Dialogue: 0,0:00:01.08,0:00:02.59,Default,,0,0,0,,“He was at ease \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:02.59,0:00:04.82,Default,,0,0,0,,“with sophisticated intellectuals \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:04.82,0:00:07.32,Default,,0,0,0,,“and with humble tentmakers. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:07.32,0:00:10.69,Default,,0,0,0,,“He was persuasive to Roman dignitaries \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:10.69,0:00:13.36,Default,,0,0,0,,“and to Phrygian peasants. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:13.36,0:00:16.57,Default,,0,0,0,,“His writings were motivating \Nto liberal Greeks \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:16.57,0:00:19.57,Default,,0,0,0,,and to conservative Jews.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:19.57,0:00:24.14,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s how the December 1, 2005, \Nissue of The Watchtower \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:24.14,0:00:28.48,Default,,0,0,0,,described the inspired writer \Nof today’s text.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:28.48,0:00:32.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Certainly, \Nthe apostle Paul was a master \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:32.02,0:00:36.52,Default,,0,0,0,,of becoming \N“all things to people of all sorts.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:36.52,0:00:39.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Please open your Bibles to Acts chapter 20. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:39.79,0:00:42.09,Default,,0,0,0,,We’re going to read verse 21. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:42.09,0:00:46.46,Default,,0,0,0,,With these words, \NPaul describes his commission as an apostle. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:46.46,0:00:49.57,Default,,0,0,0,,As we read Acts 20:21, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:49.57,0:00:52.27,Default,,0,0,0,,notice the broad scope of his territory \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:52.27,0:00:57.94,Default,,0,0,0,,and also the purpose of his ministry. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:57.94,0:01:00.21,Default,,0,0,0,,He said: \N“But I thoroughly bore witness \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:00.21,0:01:02.35,Default,,0,0,0,,“both to Jews and to Greeks \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:02.35,0:01:04.98,Default,,0,0,0,,“about repentance toward God \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:04.98,0:01:09.02,Default,,0,0,0,,and faith in our Lord Jesus.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:09.02,0:01:11.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Like the apostle Paul, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:11.02,0:01:15.79,Default,,0,0,0,,we too have a commission \Nto preach to people of all sorts. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:15.79,0:01:20.73,Default,,0,0,0,,But is it too much to ask us \Nto imitate Paul’s example? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:20.73,0:01:22.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Think about it. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:22.73,0:01:25.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Paul had the advantage \Nof being well-educated. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:25.67,0:01:29.84,Default,,0,0,0,,He was part of the privileged class \Nof Roman citizens. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:29.84,0:01:33.94,Default,,0,0,0,,He held a powerful position as a Pharisee. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:33.94,0:01:37.95,Default,,0,0,0,,None of us have those qualifications. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:37.95,0:01:40.68,Default,,0,0,0,,But are these the things that qualified Paul \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:40.68,0:01:43.15,Default,,0,0,0,,as a minister of the good news? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:43.15,0:01:46.26,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s true, \Nhis being a distinguished lawyer \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:46.26,0:01:50.73,Default,,0,0,0,,no doubt helped him to defend \Nand legally establish the good news. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:50.73,0:01:52.73,Default,,0,0,0,,But on the other hand, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:52.73,0:01:57.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Paul’s background created obstacles \Nthat he had to overcome. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:57.70,0:02:02.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Only then could he preach \Nto people of all sorts.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:02.71,0:02:05.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Paul was a Jewish Pharisee \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:05.38,0:02:09.05,Default,,0,0,0,,and that name Pharisee \Nmeans “Separated Ones.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:09.05,0:02:12.82,Default,,0,0,0,,This may refer to the fact \Nthat the Pharisees \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:12.82,0:02:17.79,Default,,0,0,0,,maintained a very strict separation \Nfrom Gentiles. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.79,0:02:22.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Then Jehovah picked Paul to be an apostle. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:22.16,0:02:24.16,Default,,0,0,0,,And to whom? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:24.16,0:02:25.93,Default,,0,0,0,,To the Gentiles. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:25.93,0:02:28.16,Default,,0,0,0,,No doubt, \NPaul had to do a lot of soul-searching \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:28.16,0:02:30.50,Default,,0,0,0,,to overcome his former prejudices \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:30.50,0:02:35.00,Default,,0,0,0,,in order to carry out \Nhis commission to preach.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:35.00,0:02:38.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Paul’s need to make major changes \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:38.27,0:02:42.31,Default,,0,0,0,,reminds me of a man \Nin North Carolina some years ago. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:42.31,0:02:45.72,Default,,0,0,0,,He served as the minister \Nof a large Methodist church \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:45.72,0:02:48.08,Default,,0,0,0,,for over 25 years; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:48.08,0:02:50.45,Default,,0,0,0,,then he came into the truth. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:50.45,0:02:54.69,Default,,0,0,0,,This man had preached hundreds, \Nif not thousands, of sermons. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:54.69,0:02:56.69,Default,,0,0,0,,With such a background, \Nyou would think \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:56.69,0:03:00.20,Default,,0,0,0,,that public speaking \Nwould be easy for him. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:00.20,0:03:04.43,Default,,0,0,0,,And yet, he said \None of the hardest things he ever had to do \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:04.43,0:03:08.30,Default,,0,0,0,,was to stand up in front \Nof the congregation in the Kingdom Hall \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:08.30,0:03:11.41,Default,,0,0,0,,and deliver a five-minute Bible reading. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:11.41,0:03:14.28,Default,,0,0,0,,No doubt, \Nthe apostle Paul’s example \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:14.28,0:03:18.28,Default,,0,0,0,,was a source of encouragement \Nto this humble brother.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:18.28,0:03:20.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Truly, \Nthe Kingdom good news \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:20.38,0:03:24.25,Default,,0,0,0,,is a message for all peoples. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:24.25,0:03:27.96,Default,,0,0,0,,But when it comes \Nto preaching the good news, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:27.96,0:03:30.43,Default,,0,0,0,,unlike many baseball caps, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:30.43,0:03:33.93,Default,,0,0,0,,one size does not fit all. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:33.93,0:03:36.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Like Paul, to be effective, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:36.13,0:03:40.67,Default,,0,0,0,,we have to be adaptable in the way \Nthat we present the good news. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:40.67,0:03:43.57,Default,,0,0,0,,So let’s consider three key qualities \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:43.57,0:03:47.24,Default,,0,0,0,,that helped to make Paul \Nan effective minister. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:47.24,0:03:49.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Paul was attentive, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:49.31,0:03:51.31,Default,,0,0,0,,he was flexible, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:51.31,0:03:53.45,Default,,0,0,0,,and he was resourceful.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:53.45,0:03:56.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Consider how he was attentive. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:56.82,0:04:01.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Paul understood the background \Nand the beliefs of his audience. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:01.82,0:04:04.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Consider what happened when he was asked \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:04.53,0:04:08.70,Default,,0,0,0,,to appear before King Agrippa II. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:08.70,0:04:12.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Please open your Bibles to Acts chapter 26. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:12.70,0:04:15.24,Default,,0,0,0,,We’re going to read verses 2 and 3, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:15.24,0:04:17.37,Default,,0,0,0,,and we notice from these verses \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:17.37,0:04:22.11,Default,,0,0,0,,that Paul first commended Agrippa \Non his being well-versed \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:22.11,0:04:26.12,Default,,0,0,0,,in the background \Nof the people he was ruling. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:26.12,0:04:30.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Acts 26:2,3, \Nit says: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:30.02,0:04:32.36,Default,,0,0,0,,“Concerning all the things \Nof which I am accused \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:32.36,0:04:34.36,Default,,0,0,0,,“by the Jews, King Agrippa, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:34.36,0:04:37.19,Default,,0,0,0,,“I consider myself happy \Nthat it is before you \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:37.19,0:04:39.76,Default,,0,0,0,,“I am to make my defense this day, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:39.76,0:04:43.43,Default,,0,0,0,,“especially because you are \Nan expert on all the customs \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:43.43,0:04:46.94,Default,,0,0,0,,“as well as the controversies \Namong the Jews. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:46.94,0:04:51.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Therefore, \NI beg you to hear me patiently.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:53.74,0:04:57.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Paul was not trying to flatter the king. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:57.58,0:05:01.25,Default,,0,0,0,,He was simply using \Nhis knowledge of his audience \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:01.25,0:05:06.76,Default,,0,0,0,,to establish a common ground \Non which he could begin to preach.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:06.76,0:05:08.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Paul was flexible. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:08.76,0:05:11.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Consider what happened \Nwhen he and Barnabas \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:11.09,0:05:13.46,Default,,0,0,0,,entered the city of Lystra to preach. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:13.46,0:05:18.13,Default,,0,0,0,,The account is recorded \Nin Acts chapter 14. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:18.13,0:05:20.50,Default,,0,0,0,,The audience that they met there in Lystra \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:20.50,0:05:24.07,Default,,0,0,0,,was totally different \Nfrom that of King Agrippa \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:24.07,0:05:28.41,Default,,0,0,0,,and the one hundred dignitaries \Nwho may have been in the group with him. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:28.41,0:05:30.41,Default,,0,0,0,,This crowd in Lystra \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:30.41,0:05:32.72,Default,,0,0,0,,was made up of a less educated \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.72,0:05:36.12,Default,,0,0,0,,and more superstitious part \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:36.12,0:05:38.35,Default,,0,0,0,,of the population. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:38.35,0:05:41.56,Default,,0,0,0,,When they healed a man \Nwho had been lame from birth, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:41.56,0:05:43.29,Default,,0,0,0,,the crowd cried out: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:43.29,0:05:46.03,Default,,0,0,0,,“The gods have become \Nlike humans and have come down to us!” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:46.03,0:05:50.43,Default,,0,0,0,,They even wanted to offer up \Nsacrifices to Paul and Barnabas. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:50.43,0:05:54.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Obviously, \NPaul could not reason with those people \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:54.94,0:05:58.11,Default,,0,0,0,,on the basis of their superstitions. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:58.11,0:06:01.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Rather, \Nhe told the crowd that he and Barnabas \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:01.18,0:06:03.65,Default,,0,0,0,,were imperfect humans just like them. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:03.65,0:06:08.68,Default,,0,0,0,,And then he turned \Ntheir attention away from puny humans \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:08.68,0:06:13.69,Default,,0,0,0,,and directed it \Nto the grand creation and our living God, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:13.69,0:06:16.46,Default,,0,0,0,,the one “who made the heaven and the earth \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:16.46,0:06:20.20,Default,,0,0,0,,and the sea and all the things in them.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:20.20,0:06:23.57,Default,,0,0,0,,And that was enough to restrain the crowd \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:23.57,0:06:26.30,Default,,0,0,0,,from offering those sacrifices.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:26.30,0:06:30.84,Default,,0,0,0,,A third quality of Paul \Nwas that he was resourceful. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:30.84,0:06:34.51,Default,,0,0,0,,If Paul had had the Ministry School book \Nback there in the first century, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:34.51,0:06:39.35,Default,,0,0,0,,we would probably say \Nthat he did well on point number 46, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:39.35,0:06:43.62,Default,,0,0,0,,“Illustrations From Familiar Situations.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:43.62,0:06:47.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Paul used common, \Neasily understood illustrations \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:47.42,0:06:52.36,Default,,0,0,0,,to clarify complex spiritual matters. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:52.36,0:06:56.47,Default,,0,0,0,,For example, \Nthe Romans were familiar with slavery. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:56.47,0:06:59.60,Default,,0,0,0,,In fact, \Nmany recipients of his letter to the Romans \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:59.60,0:07:02.27,Default,,0,0,0,,may have themselves been slaves. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:02.27,0:07:07.28,Default,,0,0,0,,So Paul used slavery to illustrate \Nthe great change in ownership \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:07.28,0:07:11.51,Default,,0,0,0,,that had taken place \Nwhen these individuals became Christians. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:11.51,0:07:13.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Romans 6:18 says: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:13.52,0:07:16.65,Default,,0,0,0,,“Yes, since you were set free from sin, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:16.65,0:07:21.02,Default,,0,0,0,,you became slaves to righteousness.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:21.02,0:07:23.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Our brothers around the world \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:23.03,0:07:26.56,Default,,0,0,0,,are showing themselves \Nto be attentive, flexible, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:26.56,0:07:31.07,Default,,0,0,0,,and resourceful as they preach \Nto people of every background imaginable. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:31.07,0:07:33.10,Default,,0,0,0,,For example, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:33.10,0:07:35.10,Default,,0,0,0,,many people in the Far East are concerned \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:35.10,0:07:37.21,Default,,0,0,0,,about things that affect them personally, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:37.21,0:07:41.78,Default,,0,0,0,,such as health, \Nchild training, and education. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:41.78,0:07:44.51,Default,,0,0,0,,So our brothers there \Neffectively use those subjects \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:44.51,0:07:46.92,Default,,0,0,0,,to begin conversations. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:46.92,0:07:49.52,Default,,0,0,0,,However, \Nthat may not work as well \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:49.52,0:07:51.79,Default,,0,0,0,,in certain cities \Nin the United States \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:51.79,0:07:54.76,Default,,0,0,0,,where people may be \Nmore concerned with corruption, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:54.76,0:07:58.33,Default,,0,0,0,,traffic congestion, and crime. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:58.33,0:08:03.03,Default,,0,0,0,,But no matter what topic \Nwe use to introduce the truth, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:03.03,0:08:05.87,Default,,0,0,0,,to be effective Bible teachers, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:05.87,0:08:10.44,Default,,0,0,0,,it is important for us \Nto remain positive and encouraging \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:10.44,0:08:14.01,Default,,0,0,0,,and to stress the practical value \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:14.01,0:08:17.11,Default,,0,0,0,,of applying Bible principles.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:17.11,0:08:19.68,Default,,0,0,0,,With the help of God’s holy spirit, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:19.68,0:08:21.88,Default,,0,0,0,,the apostle Paul was able to overcome \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:21.88,0:08:24.42,Default,,0,0,0,,personal obstacles and prejudices \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:24.42,0:08:28.16,Default,,0,0,0,,to become \Nan outstanding minister of the good news. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:28.16,0:08:31.33,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s true, \Nwe may not meet a Roman dignitary \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:31.33,0:08:35.06,Default,,0,0,0,,or a Phrygian peasant \Nas we go about our territory, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:35.06,0:08:37.07,Default,,0,0,0,,but with Jehovah’s help, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:37.07,0:08:40.84,Default,,0,0,0,,we can imitate Paul’s example \Nof an effective minister \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:40.84,0:08:45.71,Default,,0,0,0,,by being attentive, \Nflexible, and resourceful. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:45.71,0:08:48.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Why do we make this effort? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:48.08,0:08:53.08,Default,,0,0,0,,We do it because we want \Nto “become all things to people of all sorts, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:53.08,0:08:56.50,Default,,0,0,0,,so that [we] \Nmight by all possible means save some.”\N
